</div>

<div id="faq" class="container py-5">

    <h4 class="section-title mb-1">FAQ</h4>
    <h2 class="section-sub-title mb-5">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="accordion" id="accordionExample">
        <div class="accordion-item">
            <h2 class="accordion-header">
                <button class="accordion-button" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseOne" aria-expanded="true" aria-controls="collapseOne">
                    Are all new things made to deteriorate faster?
                </button>
            </h2>
            <div id="collapseOne" class="accordion-collapse collapse show" data-bs-parent="#accordionExample">
                <div class="accordion-body">
                    Not everything new is made to deteriorate faster, but some products, 
                    especially in certain industries, are designed to have a shorter lifespan—this is known as <strong>planned obsolescence.</strong> <br />
                    Companies might design products to wear out or become outdated quickly in order to encourage consumers to 
                    buy newer versions or replacements more frequently.
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="accordion-item">
            <h2 class="accordion-header">
                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseTwo" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseTwo">
                    How to make the most out of your appliance reliability?
                </button>
            </h2>
            <div id="collapseTwo" class="accordion-collapse collapse" data-bs-parent="#accordionExample">
                <div class="accordion-body">
                    <strong>
                        1.
                        Regular Maintenance
                        Cleaning:
                    </strong> Regularly clean your appliances, such as washing out the lint trap in your dryer or cleaning the coils of your refrigerator. Dust and debris can cause overheating or inefficient operation.
                    Check for wear: Look for any signs of wear, such as frayed cords or loose parts, and fix them early to avoid bigger issues.
                    Service schedules: Some appliances need professional servicing (like HVAC systems or dishwashers) on a regular basis. Follow the manufacturer's recommended schedule.<br />
                    <hr />
                    <strong>
                        2. Proper Usage
                        Follow instructions:
                    </strong>  Use your appliances according to the manual. Overloading a washing machine, using the wrong detergent, or running a refrigerator with the door open can all cause undue strain.
                    Don’t push limits: For appliances like air conditioners or dishwashers, avoid running them at max capacity all the time. Give them a break to prevent excessive wear. <br />
                    <hr />
                    <strong>3. Proper Installation</strong>
                    Ensure that your appliance is installed properly, either by a professional or following the manufacturer’s instructions. Incorrect installation can lead to inefficiency or damage.
                    Appliances that are improperly leveled, connected to the wrong power supply, or poorly ventilated can suffer long-term issues. <br />
                    <hr />
                    <strong>
                        4. Monitor Usage
                        Energy-efficient settings:
                    </strong> Many appliances have eco-friendly modes that help minimize wear and tear while saving energy.
                    Keep an eye on performance: If your appliance isn’t functioning as efficiently as it used to, address the issue sooner rather than later. This could indicate a need for repair before the problem worsens. <br />
                    <hr />
                    <strong>5. Repairs Over Replacement</strong>
                    If an appliance shows signs of malfunction, it’s often cheaper to repair than replace it immediately—especially if it's only a minor issue.
                    Having a professional inspect or repair the appliance can save you the cost of a new one and extend its life for several more years. <br />
                    <hr />
                    <strong>6. Protect from Power Surges</strong>
                    Use surge protectors or voltage regulators to protect appliances from power spikes. This is especially important for sensitive electronics like refrigerators, microwaves, or computers. <br />
                    <hr />
                    <strong>7. Keep it Cool and Dry</strong>
                    Avoid placing appliances in areas with extreme temperatures or humidity. For example, avoid putting a refrigerator or microwave in direct sunlight, or near a heater, as this can cause it to work harder or wear out more quickly.
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="accordion-item">
            <h2 class="accordion-header">
                <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseThree" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseThree">
                    What role does energy efficiency play in appliance design?
                </button>
            </h2>
            <div id="collapseThree" class="accordion-collapse collapse" data-bs-parent="#accordionExample">
                <div class="accordion-body">
                    Energy efficiency has become a key consideration in appliance design due to environmental concerns and rising energy costs. 
                    Many modern appliances are built to meet stringent energy standards, using advanced technologies like inverter motors, 
                    smart thermostats, and better insulation to reduce power consumption. This not only helps the environment but also saves 
                    consumers money on energy bills in the long run. Choosing energy-efficient models, coupled with regular maintenance, 
                    ensures that appliances work as intended without unnecessary waste.
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

</div>

